<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec41-VectorsLines" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Vectors and Lines</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      In this section, we will build the foundation of vector geometry. 
      We will learn what vectors are, how to manipulate them both algebraically and geometrically, and ultimately how to use them to construct and analyze lines in three-dimensional space. 
    </p>

    <objectives>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          After this section, students will be able to:
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            define vectors in <m>\R^2</m> and <m>\R^3</m>, and determine their components given an initial point and a terminal point.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            calculate the length of a vector.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            perform vector addition, scalar multiplication, and vector subtraction geometrically.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            construct the vector and parametric equations of a line in <m>\R^3</m> given either a point and a direction vector, or two points on the line.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            determine whether two lines in <m>\R^3</m> are parallel, intersecting, or skew, and calculate the exact point of intersection if it exists.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </objectives>
    
  </introduction>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-BasicVectorR2">
    <title>Vectors in <m>\boldsymbol{\R^2}</m> and <m>\R^3</m></title>

    <p>
      The notation <m>\R^n</m> means the set of all ordered n-tuples of real numbers. 
      Symbolically speaking, 
      <md>
        \R^n = \R \times \R \times \cdots \times \R = \left\{(x_1, x_2, \ldots, x_n) \mid x_i \in \R\right\}
      </md>
      Or, using our linear algebra notation, we can write this as
        <md>
            \R^n = \left\{ \begin{bmatrix} x_1 \\ x_2 \\ \vdots \\ x_n \end{bmatrix} \mid x_i \in \R \right\}
        </md> 
    </p>

    <p>
        Imagine we want to study <em>vector geometry</em>, then we will focus on the cases of <m>\R^2</m> and <m>\R^3</m>, since they are the most intuitive to visualize. 
        That is, 
        <md>
            \R^2 = \{\begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix} \mid x,y \in \R\} \quad\text{and}\quad \R^3 = \{\begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \\ z \end{bmatrix} \mid x,y,z \in \R\}
        </md>
    </p>

    <p>
        A <term>vector</term>, in the geometric sense, is an arrow that has a tail and a tip. 
        Let's call the tail (initial point) <m>P</m> and the tip (terminal point) <m>Q</m>. 
        Then we can write the vector as <m>\v{v} = \overrightarrow{PQ}</m>, and we draw <m>\v{v}</m> as an arrow pointing from <m>P</m> to <m>Q</m>. 
    </p>

    <figure>
      <caption>The vector <m>\v{v} = \overrightarrow{PQ}</m> in <m>\R^2</m></caption>
      <image source="sec41-BasicVector-R2.png" width="50%"></image>
    </figure>

    <note>
      <title>Why is <m>\v{v}</m> bolded but not <m>P</m> or <m>Q</m>? </title>
      <p>
        This is a notation convention. 
        There is a difference between a vector and a point (or scalar). 
        To specify the difference, we usually <alert>bold</alert> the vector notation. 
      </p>

      <p>
        For example, if you see something like <m>\v{u}</m>, then this indicates that <m>\v{u}</m> is a vector. 
        As a comparison, if you see something like <m>u</m>, then this indicates that <m>u</m> is a scalar (a number). 
      </p>

      <p>
        But why don't we bold the vector <m>\overrightarrow{PQ}</m> as <m>\v{PQ}</m>, but instead put an arrow on top of it? 
      </p>

      <p>
        That is because the arrow notation specifies the tail and the tip of the vector! 
        There is a difference between <m>\overrightarrow{PQ}</m> and <m>\overrightarrow{QP}</m>! 
        They have the opposite tail and tip, so they point in opposite directions! 
      </p>

      <p>
        Another reason why sometimes we use the arrow notation is because <em>it is super difficult to write in bold font!</em>
        This is why Richard often writes <m>\overrightarrow{\, v\, }</m> on the board to indicate the vector <m>\v{v}</m>, since he can't write in bold font easily... 
      </p>
    </note>

    <p>
      In <m>\R^2</m>, each point is represented by an ordered pair of real numbers. 
      Then we can define the <term>components</term> of a vector using the ordered pairs of the two points as follows.
    </p>

    <definition xml:id="def-ComponentsVectorR2">
      <title>Components of a Vector</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The components of <m>\v{v} = \overrightarrow{PQ}</m>, where <m>P = (a_1, b_1)</m> and <m>Q = (a_2, b_2)</m>, are the quantities
          <md>
            a = a_2 - a_1 \quad \text{($x$-component)}\, , \qquad \qquad b = b_2 - b_1 \quad \text{($y$-component)}
          </md>
          The pair of components is denoted <m>\langle a,b \rangle</m>. 
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    
    <p>
      <term>P.S.:</term> If you are a linear algebra-ist and want to use the notation of the column vectors instead, be my guest! 
      Just remember that Richard prefers the column vector notation over the sharp-y angle bracket notation (but he is teaching calculus, not linear algebra, so he will have to live with it).
    </p>

    <example>
      <p>
        Find the components of the following vectors with tail <m>P</m> and tip <m>Q</m>. 
        Then sketch the vectors.  
      </p>

      <ol marker="(a)">
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>P_1 = (1,2)</m> and <m>Q_1 = (4,6)</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>P_2 = (-4,-2)</m> and <m>Q_2 = (-1,2)</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>P_3 = (2,-1)</m> and <m>Q_3 = (-3,-1)</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>P_4 = (-2,4)</m> and <m>Q_4 = (-5,1)</m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>

      <solution>
        <p>
          We can find the components of each vector using the definition: 
          <md>
            \v{v} = \la a_2 - a_1, b_2 - b_1 \ra
          </md>
        </p>
        <ol marker="a">
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\v{v}_1 = \overrightarrow{P_1Q_1} = \la 4-1, 6-2 \ra = \la 3, 4 \ra</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\v{v}_2 = \overrightarrow{P_2Q_2} = \la -1 - (-4), 2 - (-2) \ra = \la 3, 4 \ra</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\v{v}_3 = \overrightarrow{P_3Q_3} = \la -3 - 2, -1 - (-1) \ra = \la -5, 0 \ra</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\v{v}_4 = \overrightarrow{P_4Q_4} = \la -5 - (-2), 1 - 4 \ra = \la -3, -3 \ra</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>

        <p>
          The sketches of the vectors are shown below: 
        </p>

        <figure>
          <image source="sec121-VectorComponents-Example.png" width="60%"></image>
        </figure>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <p>
      Observe that <m>\v{v}_1</m> and <m>\v{v}_2</m> are <em>parallel</em>. 
      Moreover, <m>\v{v}_2</m> is a translation of <m>\v{v}_1</m> (i.e., we can obtain <m>\v{v}_2</m> by sliding <m>\v{v}_1</m> to the left and down). 
      We call these two vectors <term>equivalent vectors</term> if one is a translation of the other.  
    </p>

    <p>
      In fact, two vectors are <term>equivalent</term> if and only if they have the same components. 
      So instead of studying millions of the same vectors in different locations, we can just study one representative vector for each group of equivalent vectors. 
    </p>

    <p>
      But which location should we choose for the representative vector? 
      To keep things easier, we usually choose the representative vector whose tail is at the origin <m>(0,0)</m>. 
      Then the tip of the vector is at the coordinate point <m>(a,b)</m>, where <m>\langle a,b \rangle</m> are the components of the vector.
      This is called the <term>position vector</term>. 
    </p>

    <example>
      <p>
        Sketch the position vectors of the vectors in the previous example. 
      </p>

      <solution>
        <p>
          The vectors in the previous example are 
          <md>
            \v{v}_1 = \v{v}_2 = \la 3, 4 \ra, \quad \v{v}_3 = \la -5, 0 \ra, \quad \v{v}_4 = \la -3, -3 \ra
          </md>
          The position vectors are sketched below. 
        </p>

         <figure>
          <image source="sec121-PositionVectors-Example.png" width="60%"></image>
        </figure>
      </solution>
    </example>
    
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-AttributesVector">
    <title>The Attributes of Vectors</title>

    <p>
      When defining a vector, it is important to note its <term>length</term> and the <term>direction</term>. 
    </p>

    <p>
      The <term>length</term> of a vector <m>\v{v}</m> is the distance from the tail to the tip. 
      This is denoted as <m>\|\v{v}\|</m>. 
    </p>

    <p>
      Given a vector <m>\v{v} = \langle a,b \rangle</m>, we can determine its length using the Pythagorean Theorem, as demonstrated in the figure below. 
    </p>

    <figure>
      <caption>The Length of the vectors <m>\v{v}_0</m> and <m>\v{v}</m></caption>
      <image source="sec41-VectorMagnitude-R2.png" width="50%">
      </image>
    </figure>

    <p>
      By the Pythagorean Theorem, we have
      <md>
        <mrow> \|\v{v}\| \amp= \sqrt{(a_1 - a_2)^2 + (b_1 - b_2)^2} </mrow>
        <mrow> \amp= \sqrt{a^2 + b^2} </mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
    
    <p>
      The magnitude of a vector is really called the <term><m>\boldsymbol{\ell^2}</m> norm</term> or the <term>Euclidean norm</term> of a vector in more advanced math courses.
      In general, norms must satisfy the following three properties: 
      <ol marker="1.">
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\|\v{v}\| \geq 0</m>, with <m>\|\v{v}\| = 0</m> if and only if <m>\v{v} = \v{0}</m>. 
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\| \lambda\v{v}\| = |\lambda|\|\v{v}\|</m> for all scalars <m>\lambda \in \R</m>. 
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\|\v{v} + \v{w}\| \leq \|\v{v}\| + \|\v{w}\|</m> for any two vectors <m>\v{v}</m> and <m>\v{w}</m>, with equallity only if <m>\v{v} = 0</m>, <m>\v{w} = 0</m>, or if <m>\v{w} = \lambda\v{v}</m> where <m>\lambda \geq 0</m>. 
            (This is the famous <term>triangle inequality</term>). 
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
      This isn't a linear algebra or functional analysis class, so we won't go deeper into norms here. 
      If you are interested, feel free to do more digging on your own (or ask Richard!). 
    </p>

    <example>
      <p>
        Find the magnitude of the vectors in the previous examples. 
      </p>

      <solution>
        <p>
          The vectors in the previous examples are
          <md>
            \v{v}_1 = \v{v}_2 = \la 3, 4 \ra, \quad \v{v}_3 = \la -5, 0 \ra, \quad \v{v}_4 = \la -3, -3 \ra
          </md>
          Then 
          <md>
            <mrow>\|\v{v}_1\| \amp= \sqrt{3^2 + 4^2} = \sqrt{25} = 5 </mrow>
            <mrow>\|\v{v}_3\| \amp= \sqrt{(-5)^2 + 0^2} = \sqrt{25} = 5 </mrow>
            <mrow>\|\v{v}_4\| \amp= \sqrt{(-3)^2 + (-3)^2} = \sqrt{18} = 3\sqrt{2} </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <p>
      Now let's discuss the <term>direction</term> of a vector. 
      The direction of a vector tells us where the vector is pointing. 
      We can indicate the direction of a vector by using the vector itself. 
      As you imagine, the length of a vector has nothing to do with its direction, so we sometimes use a <term>unit vector</term>, which is a vector of length <m>1</m>, to indicate the direction, when it is not necessary to specify length. 
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-VectorAlgebra">
    <title>Vector Algebra (Geometry Version)</title>

    <p>
      Recall we defined two basic operations for vectors: vector addition and scalar multiplication. 
      They both work component-wise. 
      Now let's investigate what these operations look like <em>geometrically</em>.
    </p>

    <p>
      <term>Vector addition</term> tells us how to <em>add two vectors</em> together. 
      Geometrically speaking, we can imagine a vector as the movement from the tail to the tip. 
      Then adding two vectors means performing the movements one after another. 
      That is, we will need to find the equivalent vector of the second vector <em>whose tail is at the tip of the first vector</em>, and the resulting vector is the vector from the tail of the first vector to the tip of the second vector. 
      This is sometimes referred to as the <term>Triangle Law</term>. 
    </p>

    <figure>
      <image source="sec41-VectorAddition-Triangle.png" width="60%"></image>
      <caption>Vector Addition using the Triangle Law</caption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      But sometimes we are given the position vectors and their tails are both at the origin (or at the same point). 
      Alternatively, rather than finding the equivalent vector of the second vector, we can construct a parallelogram using the two vectors as adjacent sides, and the resulting vector is the diagonal of the parallelogram starting from the common tail of the two vectors. 
      This is called the <term>Parallelogram Law</term>. 
    </p>

    <figure>
      <image source="sec41-VectorAddition-Parallelogram.png" width="60%"></image>
      <caption>Vector Addition using the Parallelogram Law</caption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      Now let's look at <term>scalar multiplication</term>. 
      The term <alert>scalar</alert> refers to a real number. 
      That is, scalar multiplication tells us how to multiply a vector by a real number. 
      The scalar will "scale" or "resize" the vector. 
    </p>

    <p>
      When the scalar is positive, the resulting vector points in the same direction, and the size of the vector is scaled by the scalar. 
    </p>

    <figure>
      <image source="sec41-ScalarMult-Positive.png" width="40%"></image>
      <caption>Vector Addition using the Parallelogram Law</caption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      When the scalar is negative, the resulting vector points in the opposite direction, and the size of the vector is scaled by the absolute value of the scalar. 
    </p>

    <figure>
      <image source="sec41-ScalarMult-Negative.png" width="50%"></image>
      <caption>Vector Multiplication by a Negative Scalar</caption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      But what if the scalar is zero? 
      We can quickly see that the length of the resulting vector is zero, so the resulting vector is the <term>zero vector</term>, denoted by <m>\v{0}</m>. 
      We can imagine the zero vector  has the tail and tip at the same point, which means it doesn't have a specific direction. 
      Alternatively, we can say that the zero vector points in <em>all</em> directions. 
    </p>
    
    <p>
      Once we have vector addition and scalar multiplication defined, we can subtract two vectors. 
      Recall subtraction is really the same thing as adding the opposite. 
      That is, 
      <md>
        \v{v} - \v{w} = \v{v} + (-\v{w})
      </md>
      Graphically, we can find <m>\v{v} - \v{w}</m> as follows:
    </p>

    <figure>
      <image source="sec41-VectorSubtraction.png" width="80%"></image>
      <caption>Vector Subtraction</caption>
    </figure>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="subsec-LinesR3">
        <title>Lines in <m>\R^3</m></title>

        <p>
        Remember back when you first learned about lines in <m>\R^2</m>, you probably remember that we need both <em>the slope</em> and <em>a point on the line</em> to define a line. 
        <ul marker="">
            <li>
            <p>
                The slope tells us the direction of the line. 
                Yet knowing just the slope doesn't tell us a unique line... 
                There can be thousands of parallel lines with the same slope! 
            </p>
            </li>
            <li>
            <p>
                A point on the line can pin down the location of the line. 
                Yet knowing just a point on the line doesn't tell us the direction of the line... 
                We can draw infinitely many lines through a single point!  
            </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
        This is also the case in <m>\R^3</m>! 
        In order to determine a line in <m>\R^3</m>, we need to know both the direction of the line and a point on the line. 
        </p>

        <p>
        Unlike stuff in <m>\R^2</m>, there is no "slope" in <m>\R^3</m> to represent the direction of a line, since "slope" is a concept that only works in two dimensions. 
        Instead, we use a vector to represent the direction of the line. 
        </p>

        <p>
        We can find a point in <m>\R^3</m> just fine, since points in <m>\R^3</m> are represented by ordered triples. 
        </p>

        <p>
        Hence, a line in <m>\R^3</m> is determined by a point <m>P_0 = (x_0, y_0, z_0)</m> on the line and a direction vector <m>\v{v} = \begin{bmatrix} a \\ b \\ c \end{bmatrix}</m>. 
        </p>

        <definition xml:id="def-lines-3d">
        <title>Equation of a Line in <m>\R^3</m></title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The line <m>\c{L}</m> through <m>P_0 = (x_0, y_0, z_0)</m> in the direction of <m>\v{d} = \begin{bmatrix} a \\ b \\ c \end{bmatrix}</m> is described by 
                <md>
                    \v{p} = \v{p}_0 + t \v{d} = \begin{bmatrix} x_0 \\ y_0 \\ z_0 \end{bmatrix} + t \begin{bmatrix} a \\ b \\ c \end{bmatrix}
                </md>
                where <m>\v{p}_0 = \begin{bmatrix} x_0 \\ y_0 \\ z_0 \end{bmatrix}</m>.
            </p>

            <p>
                Alternatively, we can rewrite the equation in its <term>parametric form</term>:
                <md>
                    \v{p} = \begin{bmatrix} x_0 + at \\ y_0 + bt \\ z_0 + ct \end{bmatrix}
                </md>
                where the parameter <m>t</m> takes on values <m>-\infty \lt t \lt \infty</m>. 
            </p>
        </statement>
        </definition>

        <figure>
        <image source="sec41-Line3D-Diagram.png" width="75%"></image>
        <caption>The line <m>\v{p} = \v{p}_0 + t \v{d}</m> in <m>\R^3</m></caption>
        </figure>

        <p>
            Observe that the parametric form specify the <m>x</m>-, <m>y</m>-, and <m>z</m>-coordinates of the points on the line as functions of the parameter <m>t</m>. 
            These three parametric equations is itself a linear function in the parameter <m>t</m>! 
        </p>

        <example>
            <p>
                Find an equation of the line that passes through the point <m>P_0 = (1,2,4)</m> in the direction of <m>\v{v} = \begin{bmatrix} 5 \\ -3 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}</m>. 
            </p>

            <solution>
                <p>
                    We are given <m>\v{p}_0 = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \\ 4 \end{bmatrix}</m>. 
                    Therefore, an equation of the line is 
                    <md>
                        \v{p} = \v{p}_0 + t \v{d} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \\ 4 \end{bmatrix} + t \begin{bmatrix} 5 \\ -3 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}
                    </md>
                    for <m>-\infty \lt t \lt \infty</m>. 
                </p>
                
                <p>
                    Alternatively, we can write the equation in its parametric form:
                     <md>
                        \v{p} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 + 5t \\ 2 - 3t \\ 4 + t \end{bmatrix} 
                    </md>
                    for <m>-\infty \lt t \lt \infty</m>. 
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <p>
        Back in algebra 2, you may also have learned that <em>two points</em> can also determine a line in <m>\R^2</m>. 
        This is also true in <m>\R^3</m>. 
        The trick here is to determine the direction vector using the two points. 
        </p>

        <example>
        <p>
            Find an equation of the line that passes through the points <m>P = (-2,0,-2)</m> and <m>Q = (4,3,7)</m>. 
        </p>

        <hint>
            <p>
            To find an equation of a line, we need a point on the line and a direction vector. 
            So there are really things we need to find out. 
            </p>

            <p>
            The easier part is to find a point on the line (we are given two points on the line!)
            </p>

            <p>
            The slightly trickier part is to find a direction vector. 
            Can we find a vector parallel to the line using the two points? 
            </p>
        </hint>

        <solution>
            <p>
            A directional vector is <m>\overrightarrow{PQ}</m>. 
            Then we obtain
            <md>
                \v{d} = \overrightarrow{PQ} = \begin{bmatrix} 4-(-2) \\ 3-0 \\ 7-(-2) \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 6 \\ 3 \\ 9 \end{bmatrix}
            </md>
            We can use either point <m>P</m> or <m>Q</m> as the point on the line. 
            Using point <m>P</m>, we have <m>\v{p}_0 = \begin{bmatrix} -2 \\ 0 \\ -2 \end{bmatrix}</m>. 
            Therefore, an equation of the line is 
            <md>
                \v{p} = \v{p}_0 + t \v{d} = \begin{bmatrix} -2 \\ 0 \\ -2 \end{bmatrix} + t \begin{bmatrix} 6 \\ 3 \\ 9 \end{bmatrix}
            </md>
            for <m>-\infty \lt t \lt \infty</m>. 
            The corresponding parametric form is 
            <md>
                \v{p} = \begin{bmatrix} -2 + 6t \\ 0 + 3t \\ -2 + 9t \end{bmatrix}
            </md>
            for <m>-\infty \lt t \lt \infty</m>. 
            </p>
        </solution>
        </example>

        <p>
            Recall back in <m>\R^2</m>, two lines are either parallel or they intersect at a single point (assuming the lines are not essentially the same line). 
            In <m>\R^3</m>, if two lines are parallel, then the direction vectors should be parallel, and hence they are scalar multiples of each other. 
            But how do we know if two lines intersect, and if so, how do we find the point of intersection?
        </p>

        <example>
        <p>
            Determine whether the lines <m>\v{p}_1 = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ -3 \\ 5 \end{bmatrix} + t \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \\ -1 \end{bmatrix}</m> and <m>\v{p}_2 = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ 7 \end{bmatrix} + s \begin{bmatrix} -2 \\ 1 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix}</m> intersect, and if so, find the point of intersection.
        </p>

        <hint>
            <p>
            Let's just assume that the two lines intersect. 
            If two lines intersect, then they must intersect at a single point.
            </p>

            <p>
            Now put on your algebra 2 hat and think about how to find the point of intersection of two lines in <m>\R^2</m>. 
            (You would set the two equations equal to each other and solve for <m>x</m>!)
            </p>
        </hint>

        <solution>
            <p>
                The lines intersect if there exist parameter values <m>t</m> and <m>s</m> such that
                <md>
                    <mrow>\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ -3 \\ 5 \end{bmatrix} + t \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \\ -1 \end{bmatrix} \amp= \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ 7 \end{bmatrix} + s \begin{bmatrix} -2 \\ 1 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                    <mrow>\begin{bmatrix} 1+t \\ -3+2t \\ 5-t \end{bmatrix} \amp= \begin{bmatrix} -2s \\ s \\ 7+3s \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                </md>
                Equating corresponding components, we get
                <md>
                    \begin{cases}
                    1 + t = -2s \\
                    -3 + 2t = s \\
                    5 - t = 7 + 3s
                    \end{cases}
                </md>
                This is a system of three equations with two variables!  
                We can solve this system using the augmented matrix! 
            </p>

            <p>
                The agumented matrix of the system is
                <md>
                \begin{pmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \amp \mid \amp -1 \\ 2 \amp -1 \amp \mid \amp 3 \\ -1 \amp -3 \amp \mid \amp 2 \end{pmatrix}
                </md>
                Row reducing this matrix, we get
                <md>
                \begin{pmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp \mid \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp \mid \amp -1 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp \mid \amp 0 \end{pmatrix} 
                </md>
                From here we can read off the solution <m>t = 1</m>, <m>s = -1</m>.
            </p>

            <p>
                To find the point of intersection we substitute <m>t = 1</m> into the equation for <m>\v{p}_1</m> (or <m>s = -1</m> into <m>\v{p}_2</m>) to obtain
                <md>
                    \begin{bmatrix} 1+1 \\ -3+2(1) \\ 5-1 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ -1 \\ 4 \end{bmatrix}
                </md>
                The point of intersection is the terminal point of this vector, that is, <m>\lp 2, -1, 4 \rp</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
        </example>

        <example>
        <p>
            Determine whether the lines <m>\v{p}_1 = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ -2 \\ 4 \end{bmatrix} + t \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 3 \\ -1 \end{bmatrix}</m> and <m>\v{p}_2 = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 3 \\ -3 \end{bmatrix} + s \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 1 \\ 4 \end{bmatrix}</m> are parallel, intersect, or neither. 
        </p>

        <hint>
            <p>
            Observe that the direction vectors are <m>\v{v}_1 = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 3 \\ -1 \end{bmatrix}</m> and <m>\v{v}_2 = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 1 \\ 4 \end{bmatrix}</m> are not multiples of each other, so the lines are not parallel.
            </p>

            <p>
            Then the two other possibilities are that the lines intersect or they are skew. 
            We haven't discussed how to check if two lines are skew, but we can check if they intersect. 
            So the question becomes: do the two lines intersect? 
            </p>
        </hint>

        <solution>
            <p>
                If the two lines intersect, then there exist parameter values <m>t</m> and <m>s</m> such that
                <md>
                    <mrow>\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ -2 \\ 4 \end{bmatrix} + t \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 3 \\ -1 \end{bmatrix} \amp= \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 3 \\ -3 \end{bmatrix} + s \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 1 \\ 4 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                    <mrow>\begin{bmatrix} 1+t \\ -2+3t \\ 4 - t \end{bmatrix} \amp= \begin{bmatrix} 2s \\ 3 + s \\ -3 + 4s \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                </md>
                Equating corresponding components, we get
                <md>
                    \begin{cases}
                    1 + t = 2s \\
                    -2 + 3t = 3 + s \\
                    4 - t = -3 + 4s
                    \end{cases}
                </md>
                The augmented matrix of this system is 
                <md>
                    \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp -2 \amp mid \amp -1 \\ 3 \amp -1 \amp \mid \amp 5 \\ -1 \amp -4 \amp \mid \amp -7 \end{bmatrix}
                </md>
                Row reducing this matrix we get
                <md>
                    \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp \mid \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp \mid \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp \mid \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}
                </md>
                Observe that a pivot position appears in the rightmost column, which implies that the system is inconsistent. 
            </p>

            <p>
                That is, there are no parameter values <m>t</m> and <m>s</m> such that the two lines intersect. 
                But they are not parallel either, so what are they? 
            </p>

            <p>
                It turns out that these two lines are <term>skew lines</term>: they do not intersect and are not parallel. 
                They are not coplanar.
                The figure below shows the sketch of these two lines. 
            </p>

            <figure>
            <caption>Line <m>\v{p}_1</m> (blue) and Line <m>\v{p}_2</m> (red)</caption>
            <sidebyside width="80%">
            <interactive xml:id="sage-skew-lines-simple" platform="sage" width="100%" aspect="1:1">
                <slate surface="sage">
                    var('t, s')
                    
                    # 1. Define the Lines
                    # Note: We use parens in comments to avoid XML parsing errors
                    # r1(t) = (1, -2, 4) + t(1, 3, -1)
                    line1 = parametric_plot3d(
                        [1 + t, -2 + 3*t, 4 - t], 
                        (t, -2, 4), 
                        color='blue', thickness=3
                    )
                    
                    # r2(s) = (0, 3, -3) + s(2, 1, 4)
                    line2 = parametric_plot3d(
                        [0 + 2*s, 3 + s, -3 + 4*s], 
                        (s, -1, 3), 
                        color='red', thickness=3
                    )

                    # 2. Axes Setup
                    x_len, y_len, z_len = 6, 8, 8
                    
                    axes_arrows = (
                        arrow3d((0,0,0), (x_len,0,0), color='black', width=1) +
                        arrow3d((0,0,0), (0,y_len,0), color='black', width=1) +
                        arrow3d((0,0,0), (0,0,z_len), color='black', width=1)
                    )
                    
                    axes_labels = (
                        text3d("x", (x_len + 0.2, 0, 0), color='black') +
                        text3d("y", (0, y_len + 0.2, 0), color='black') +
                        text3d("z", (0, 0, z_len + 0.2), color='black')
                    )

                    # 3. Ticks
                    ticks = Graphics()
                    tick_size = 0.2
                    
                    for i in range(1, x_len):
                        ticks += line3d([(i, -tick_size, 0), (i, tick_size, 0)], color='black')
                    for i in range(1, y_len):
                        ticks += line3d([(-tick_size, i, 0), (tick_size, i, 0)], color='black')
                    for i in range(1, z_len):
                        ticks += line3d([(0, -tick_size, i), (0, tick_size, i)], color='black')

                    # 4. Show Everything
                    show(line1 + line2 + axes_arrows + axes_labels + ticks, frame=False)
                </slate>
            </interactive>
            </sidebyside>
        </figure>
        </solution>
        </example>
    </subsection>

</section>